<Author>Joolzief
<Content>Perfect Break After much reading and research I booked the Barcelona Center for a 3 night break for my partners 40th birthday. I chose the hotel for its location, rating and cost. We were both delighted with the hotel, room and facilities. It was calm, peaceful and very comfortable. We had a lovely big room on the 5th floor overlooking the Calle des Balmes with a little balcony and floor to ceiling windows. The bathroom was fabulous with a separate bath and wet room. The beds are firm but fine. The TV wasn't working properly and couldn't get music to listen to while getting ready to go out or when back in. Also no tea/coffee faclilties in the room which I would have liked. Breakfast was included in the deal (otherwise expensive). It had a variety of hot and cold food, great coffee, plenty fresh fruit and the usual breads and cereals etc. It is about a 10 minute walk/ 20 minute stroll from the Plaza Catalunya and the top end of the Ramblas. From the roof terrace you can see the Sagrada Familia (25 minute walk) and Mont Juic. Best parts for us are the Eixample cafes and bars for tapas etc. The Born/Sant Pere area for exploring and shopping.The Gothic quarter for strolling round and for a bit of an edgy experience the Lower Raval. We found ourselves in a street (Il Roberador) which was pretty grim and for me - on the wrong side of scary. We were warned to stay away by some random guy as we obviously stuck out like typical tourists. It was wall to wall prostitutes, dealers and users, not to mention the gangs (one guy banging some metal piping against the wall as we approached!). My heart was certainly racing a bit. However we survived and a bit of sense and caution is advised. We loved Barcelona. What a great place. The Aerobus is a little over 4 euros to the City Centre. A taxi about 21 Euros (including 1 case and a supplement of 3 Euros). The Tourist bus is a great way to see other parts of the City which you can hop on and off and change routes (red and blue). The Nou Camp (17 euros is well worth a visit). But the best way is to walk and sit in pavement cafes with some Cava and Tapas (weather permitting). 
